The '''South Africa national soccer team''' represents [[South Africa]] in men's international [[association football|football]] and is run by the [[South African Football Association]], the governing body for [[football in South Africa]]. Nicknamed '''Bafana Bafana''' (The Boys in [[Zulu language|Zulu]]), the team plays at various stadiums around the country. The team is a member of both [[FIFA]] and the [[Confederation of African Football]] (CAF), is one of the most well-supported national sides in Africa,<ref>{{Cite journal | title=Supporters' perceived brand equity of the Bafana Bafana National Football Team of South Africa {{!}} African Journal for Physical Health Education, Recreation and Dance | journal=African Journal for Physical Health Education, Recreation and Dance | date=June 2013 | volume=19 | issue=2 | pages=324–335 | url=https://journals.co.za/doi/abs/10.10520/EJC137202 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240404074110/https://journals.co.za/doi/abs/10.10520/EJC137202 | access-date=23 December 2024 | archive-date=4 April 2024 | last1=Mahlangu | first1=H. B. | last2=Dlodlo | first2=N. | last3=Mokoena | first3=B. A. }}</ref> and are recognised by their traditional yellow-green kits.

Having played their first match in 1906, South Africa returned to the world stage in 1992, after sixteen years of being banned from [[FIFA]], and forty years of effective suspension due to the [[apartheid]] system.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.fifa.com/about-fifa/news/y=2004/m=10/news=from-apartheid-the-world-cup-four-decades-the-sporting-life-south-afri-94531.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170210183231/http://www.fifa.com/about-fifa/news/y=2004/m=10/news=from-apartheid-the-world-cup-four-decades-the-sporting-life-south-afri-94531.html | url-status=dead | archive-date=10 February 2017 | publisher=FIFA | title=From apartheid to the World Cup – four decades in the sporting life of South Africa | date=27 October 2004 | access-date=1 September 2017 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> South Africa have qualified for the [[FIFA World Cup]] three times: [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998]], [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002]] and [[2026 FIFA World Cup|2026]], in addition to qualifying as hosts of the 2010 tournament, becoming the first African nation to do so. Despite defeating [[France national football team|France]] 2–1 in their final game of the group stage, they failed to progress from the first round of the tournament, becoming the first host nation in the history of the FIFA World Cup to exit in the group stage, followed by [[Qatar national football team|Qatar]] in 2022.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2010/8814195.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=England slip to worst Cup ranking | date=13 July 2010 | access-date=1 December 2011 <!--DASHBot--> | archive-date=29 December 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181229103711/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2010/8814195.stm | url-status=live }}</ref> As of January 2026, the team is ranked 60th in [[FIFA]] overall.

South Africa's most significant achievement came in [[1996 African Cup of Nations|1996]] when they hosted and won the [[Africa Cup of Nations]] (AFCON). They reached the final again in 1998 but were defeated by Egypt.